<p id="fs-idp32184800">(a)<span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
</p><span data-alt="This structure shows a carbon atom double bonded to two oxygen atoms, each of which has two lone pairs of electrons." data-type="media" id="fs-idm35689072">
<img alt="This structure shows a carbon atom double bonded to two oxygen atoms, each of which has two lone pairs of electrons." data-media-type="image/jpeg" id="[redacted for uniqueness]" src="/resources/27df3f8404cacaf02741773e0b28767d57fa4e95"/>
</span><p id="[redacted for uniqueness]"><span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
(b)<span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
</p><span data-alt="The right structure of this pair shows a carbon atom with one lone pair of electrons triple bonded to an oxygen with one lone pair of electrons." data-type="media" id="fs-idp52448512">
<img alt="The right structure of this pair shows a carbon atom with one lone pair of electrons triple bonded to an oxygen with one lone pair of electrons." data-media-type="image/jpeg" id="[redacted for uniqueness]" src="/resources/c1886daeb3af0f88c21c92eb795b54ac155a19f7"/>
</span><p id="[redacted for uniqueness]"><span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
CO has the strongest carbon-oxygen bond because there is a triple bond joining C and O. CO<sub>2</sub> has double bonds.</p>
</div></div><div data-type="solution" id="fs-idp23408944-solution"><a class="os-number" href="7-exercises#fs-idp23408944">51</a><span class="os-divider">. </span><div class="os-solution-container">
<p id="fs-idm21325744">(a) H: 0, Cl: 0; (b) C: 0, F: 0; (c) P: 0, Cl 0; (d) P: 0, F: 0</p>
</div></div><div data-type="solution" id="fs-idp25221456-solution"><a class="os-number" href="7-exercises#fs-idp25221456">53</a><span class="os-divider">. </span><div class="os-solution-container">
<p id="fs-idm369848352">Cl in Cl<sub>2</sub>: 0; Cl in BeCl<sub>2</sub>: 0; Cl in ClF<sub>5</sub>: 0</p>
</div></div><div data-type="solution" id="fs-idp137881216-solution"><a class="os-number" href="7-exercises#fs-idp137881216">55</a><span class="os-divider">. </span><div class="os-solution-container">
<p id="fs-idp124490112">(a)<span data-type="newline"><br/></span>
</p><span data-alt="Two Lewis structures are shown with a double-headed arrow in between. The left structure shows an oxygen atom with one lone pair of electrons single bonded to an oxygen atom with three lone pairs of electrons. It is also double bonded to an oxygen atom with two lone pairs of electrons. The symbols and numbers below this structure read, “( 0 ), ( positive 1 ), ( negative 1 ).” The phrase, “Formal charge,” and a right-facing arrow lie to the left of this structure. The right structure appears as a mirror image of the left and the symbols and numbers below this structure read, “( negative 1 ), ( positive 1 ), ( 0 ).”" data-type="media" id="fs-idp9590704">
<img alt="Two Lewis structures are shown with a double-headed arrow in between. The left structure shows an oxygen atom with one lone pair of electrons single bonded to an oxygen atom with three lone pairs of electrons. It is also double bonded to an oxygen atom with two lone pairs of electrons. The symbols and numbers below this structure read, “( 0 ), ( positive 1 ), ( negative 1 ).” The phrase, “Formal charge,” and a right-facing arrow lie to the left of this structure. The right structure appears as a mirror image of the left and the symbols and numbers below this structure read, “( negative 1 ), ( positive 1 ), ( 0 ).”" data-media-type="image/jpeg" id="[redacted for uniqueness]" src="/resources/b742972d41310d0f1ff4a2b2e2f66f115178714c"/>
